      "summary": "Boundary functions mix raw error returns with wrapped/contextual errors, creating inconsistent failure contracts.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/config/wireguard.go",
        "goseg/click/backup/service.go",
        "goseg/docker/lifecycle/lifecycle.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "In `goseg/config/wireguard.go`, `GetWgConf` and `CreateDefaultWGConf` return raw underlying errors (`return wgConf, err`, `return err`) for I/O/encode failures without operation context.",
        "In `goseg/click/backup/service.go`, `backupAgent` returns `err` directly from `executeClickCommandForBackup`, while nearby failures are wrapped with command/component context before returning.",
        "In `goseg/docker/lifecycle/lifecycle.go`, several container runtime helpers (`createAndStartContainer`, parts of `GetShipStatus`, and other wrappers) return raw `err` despite the surrounding flow being heavily contextualized."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Establish a shared boundary error pattern (for example, wrap all external I/O/command failures with `%w` and a consistent operation prefix) and apply it across these modules. This improves logs, `errors.Is`/`errors.As` usability, and failure triage consistency.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "error_wrapping_inconsistency"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "mixed_fatal_error_strategy_in_bootstrap",
      "summary": "Critical startup paths use hard process termination instead of a consistent error propagation contract.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/main.go",
        "goseg/system/wifi.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "In `goseg/main.go`, `init()` executes `panic(err)` when embedded content setup fails (`fs.Sub` error), skipping normal error reporting and shutdown paths.",
        "In `goseg/main.go`, `killSwitch()` calls `os.Exit(0)` on debug mode, terminating the process directly from a loop routine instead of returning an error through caller control.",
        "The same startup layer otherwise uses normal `return`/logging-based error handling for other subsystem failures, so fatal handling strategy is inconsistent across adjacent startup code paths."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Refactor bootstrap to keep one failure contract: return structured errors from initialization entry points, route them through a single central error handler/logger, and avoid direct `panic`/`os.Exit` in favor of cancellation/cleanup-aware shutdown.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "fatal_error_strategy_drift"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "No shared error-boundary policy across subsystem interfaces, causing inconsistent wrapping and surfacing behavior.",
      "Mixed process-level termination semantics in startup/runtime orchestration rather than a centralized error contract."
    ],
    "likely_symptoms": [
      "Error diagnostics lose root-cause chainability (`errors.Is`/`errors.As` less useful) across modules.",
      "Debug startup behavior is harder to reason about because fatal and recoverable failures are handled inconsistently."
    ],
    "possible_false_positives": [
      "Some raw error returns in lower-level routines may be intentional to preserve original errors for upstream classification, but this is not applied consistently."
    ]
  }
